  <section class="consulting-flow" aria-label="Consulting copy">
    <div class="consulting-block consulting-block--lead" data-label="What I do">
      <p class="consulting-subhead">Perspective</p>

      <p>I help people and organizations make sense of context, evidence, and competing priorities &ndash; bringing clearer thinking, stronger grounding, and practical direction to complex work. After enough time working at the intersection of organizations, tools, and human judgment, I&rsquo;ve found myself at a unique <span class="consulting-tooltip"><a class="consulting-subtle-link consulting-hover-note" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrange_point" data-note="A point where competing pulls balance." aria-label="Lagrange point: A point where competing pulls balance.">Lagrange point</a></span> between disciplines and perspectives. That vantage is what I bring.</p>

      <p class="consulting-subhead">Working with knots</p>

      <p>I&rsquo;ve gathered a set of useful tools along the way, and made a few of my own. Most of my consulting tools are for handling <em>knots</em>: places where the grain runs in several directions at once, and the next cut is not obvious.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="consulting-block consulting-arrangement" data-label="What to Expect" aria-label="Consulting arrangement">
      <p>Most engagements start with a paid &ldquo;thought sparring&rdquo; conversation: <span class="consulting-price">$350 for a 60&ndash;90 minute call.</span> I send a few prep questions a day or two ahead. The purpose of the call is to understand the grain of the problem and find the next cut, while giving you a sense of whether you&rsquo;re <a class="consulting-quiet-link" href="https://stephango.com/in-good-hands">in good hands</a>.</p>

      <p>I only book the call if I&rsquo;m confident I can deliver more than $350 in value to you. If I can&rsquo;t, I&rsquo;ll tell you, and where I can, point you to someone who fits better.</p>

      <p>If we want to keep going past the first call, scope and rate are something we agree on in writing.</p>
    </section>

    <div class="consulting-block" data-label="Getting Started">
      <p>To start, send me a short or long note about the knot you&rsquo;re working on. Email or DM is fine. I&rsquo;ll ask follow-up questions to figure out whether I can be useful before either of us puts time or money down. The more context you share, the better we can decide, and the better I can research/prepare if we want to move forward.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="consulting-more-knots" aria-labelledby="more-on-knots">
      <h2 id="more-on-knots">More on knots</h2>

      <p>A knot begins as a branch.</p>

      <p>Each year the tree lays down another ring of wood around its base beneath the bark. Slowly the trunk thickens around the living branch, swallowing it beneath new layers of growth while keeping it alive inside the tree.</p>

      <p>If we could watch the process sped up, the tree would look strangely animate. Bark splitting. Seams opening. New wood slowly climbing over old wood. The whole trunk widening around old decisions it can no longer undo. Meanwhile the buried branch continues its quiet work somewhere inside the trunk, carrying water upward toward leaves out beyond the visible bark.</p>

      <p class="consulting-asterism" aria-hidden="true">* * *</p>

      <p>The grain has to negotiate this situation. The tree keeps growing, but from this point forward the fibers have to take the long way around.</p>

      <p>They crowd together. Cross paths. Change direction abruptly. Sometimes the wood hardens around the knot, making your tools skate uselessly, no matter how sharp, across the surface. Sometimes the fibers tear loose all at once and leave a crater where a smooth cut was supposed to be. Wood that looked calm a few inches ago suddenly makes your plane act like a shopping cart with one bad wheel. It&rsquo;s a bad feeling when you hit a knot!</p>

      <p>This is usually where people begin blaming their tools.</p>

      <p>You learn to read ahead a little.</p>

      <p class="consulting-asterism" aria-hidden="true">* * *</p>

      <p>This habit of reading carries over into the rest of my work.</p>

      <p>Most difficult situations are not difficult because nobody is smart enough or trying hard enough. They are difficult because too many realities are occupying the same space at the same time. Deadlines. Institutional habits. Public distrust. Budget limits. Exhausted staff.</p>

      <p>The grain starts moving in several directions at once.</p>

      <p>My work is to read the grain, describe the knot, and help you decide what comes next.</p>

      <p class="consulting-asterism" aria-hidden="true">* * *</p>

      <p class="consulting-tight-lines">Sometimes the answer is a careful cut.<br>
      Sometimes reinforcement.<br>
      Sometimes redesign.<br>
      Sometimes leaving the knot exactly where it is.</p>

      <p class="consulting-end-ornament" aria-hidden="true">&#10086;</p>
